Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
fixACLimitViolation(25.10)                          fixACLimitViolation(25.10)

Name
       fixACLimitViolation  -  Repairs  violations  associated with AC current
       density, wire-self-heat, Joules heat, or electromigration, mostly in  a
       postRoute stage

Syntax
       fixACLimitViolation

       [-help]

       [-excludeIO {true | false}]

       [-excludeNetFile <filename>]

       [-fixNetCategory {dataOnly | clockOnly | clockAndData}]

       [-fixingMethod  {route_rule  |  down_size  |  buffer | size_or_buffer |
       route_size_or_buffer}]

       [-postCTS]

       [-selectNetFile <filename>]

       [-useReportFile <filename>]

       [-useSegmentBasedNDR {true | false}]

       Repairs violations associated with AC current density,  wire-self-heat,
       Joules  heat,  or electromigration, mostly in a postRoute stage. Fixing
       methods are applying routing rules,  downsizing  drivers  or  adding  a
       buffer  to split up the net load on the violated nets. Use this command
       in conjunction with the verifyACLimit command. The  verifyACLimit  com-
       mand  can mark the violating net for the fixACLimitViolation command to
       repair, and it can generate the report  file  that  fixACLimitViolation
       can read.

        The fixACLimitViolation command only applies a single fixing method to
       fix  EM  violations. You can select the fixing method by specifying the
       -fixingMethod parameter. If the method is not  specified,  the  command
       will  fix  EM violations by setting route rules on violating nets.  For
       example, the following usage will apply route rules for both clock  and
       data nets while excluding nets with I/O pins:

       fixACLimitViolation -fixNetCategory clockAndData -excludeIO true

       Before running fixACLimitViolation, you can generate an incoming EM vi-
       olation report using the verifyACLimit command. This operation will en-
       sure  that  the appropriate data for fixACLimitViolation is included in
       the violation report.  After that, this report should be provided as an
       input to fixACLimitViolation using the  -useReportFile  parameter.  The
       following is an example of the sequence of operations:

       verifyACLimit -report beforeFix.rpt -view hold_view

       fixACLimitViolation -useReportFile beforeFix.rpt

       verifyACLimit -report afterFix.rpt -view hold_view

       By  default,  verifyACLimit  will  calculate EM currents using the hold
       view.  This means that verifyACLimit will internally invoke a hold tim-
       ing update.  If it is desired to  maintain  the  current  setup  timing
       graph  in  memory for use after EM fixing, the -forceHoldView parameter
       should be provided to verifyACLimit so  that  the  hold  timing  update
       doesn't  nullify  the  setup timing graph.  Below is an example of this
       scenario:

       timeDesign -postRoute

       verifyACLimit -report beforeFix.rpt -forceHoldView

       fixACLimitViolation -useReportFile beforeFix.rpt

       verifyACLimit -report afterFix.rpt -forceHoldView

       Note:  It is important to set the right switching  activity  factor  on
       the  nets  before  using  the  verifyACLimit  command.   Refer  to  the
       set_power_analysis_mode, set_default_switching_activity and set_switch-
       ing_activity commands for further details on the default  behaviors  of
       the software and how to modify them. The example below shows how to set
       the  global switching activity for verifying and fixing AC limit viola-
       tions.

       set_default_switching_activity -global_activity 0.2

       propagate_activity -set_net_freq true

       verifyACLimit -use_db_freq -report em.report

       fixACLimitViolation -useReportFile em.report

       Alternatively, verifyACLimit -toggle parameter can  be  used  for  more
       pessimistic analysis. In this case, modifying set_default_switching_ac-
       tivity is not needed. The following is an example of forcing every sig-
       nal net to toggle at 50% of the clock rate:

       verifyACLimit -toggle 0.5 -report em.report

       fixACLimitViolation -useReportFile em.report

       See verifyACLimit for further command parameters and usage.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes type and default in-
              formation for each fixACLimitViolation parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man fixACLimitViolation

       -excludeIO {true | false}
              If set to true, excludes nets connected to I/O pins during  vio-
              lation fixing.

              Default: false

       -excludeNetFile <filename>
              Specifies a file that contains the names of nets to exclude from
              AC limit violation repair.

       -fixNetCategory { dataOnly | clockOnly | clockAndData}
              Specifies  fixing net types. For dataOnly, fixes data nets only.
              If clockOnly is specified, fixes clock nets. If clockAndData  is
              specified, fixes clock and data nets.

              Note:  For clock nets, only route rules will be used for fixing.
              Downsizing or buffering will not be used.

              Default: dataOnly

       -fixingMethod {route_rule | down_size | buffer | size_or_buffer |
       route_size_or_buffer}
              Specifies the fixing method for correcting  EM  violations.  You
              can specify any of the following:

              * route_rule: Apply routing rules to signal EM violating nets.

              * down_size: Apply driver cell downsizing to signal EM violating
                nets.

              * buffer: Apply buffering to signal EM violating nets.

              *

                size_or_buffer:   Apply  sizing or buffering to signal EM vio-
                lating nets. This option is  only  applicable  to  data  nets.
                Clock nets will be skipped from sizing or buffering.

              * route_size_or_buffer:  Apply  routing, sizing, or buffering to
                signal EM violating nets. Routing can be applied to both clock
                and data nets. However, sizing or buffering will only  be  ap-
                plied to data nets.

              Default: route_rule

       -postCTS
              If  specified,  enables fix for the clock nets, for postCTS DBs.
              This parameter should be used only with  -fixNetCategory  clock-
              Only.

              Default: omitted

       -selectNetFile <fileName>
              Specifies  a  file  that contains the names of nets for which to
              perform AC limit violation repair.

       -useReportFile <filename>
              Reads the verifyACLimit report, and uses the violation  informa-
              tion from the report file to set up a proper routing rules. This
              is recommended for the best fixing performance.

       -useSegmentBasedNDR {true | false}
              Enables/disables segment-based route rules. If set to true, gen-
              erates  and  applies segment-based route rules for fixing viola-
              tions. This approach enables you to specify  the  desired  width
              and distance for each layer of the violated net.

              Default: true

Examples
              * The  following  command  performs buffering only, for the nets
                specified in the netFile.txt only:

                fixACLimitViolation -fixingMethod buffer -selectNetFile  "net-
                File.txt"

              * To use downsizing, excluding nets with I/O pins:

                fixACLimitViolation -fixingMethod down_size -excludeIO true

              * To fix both clock and data nets with route rules:

                fixACLimitViolation -fixNetCategory clockAndData

              * The  following  example shows how to feed verifyACLimit report
                through the -useReportFile parameter.

                fixACLimitViolation -useReportFile em.report

